    mf = midi.MidiFile()
    mf.open(filename)
    mf.read()
    mf.close()
    s = midi.translate.midiFileToStream(mf)
    s.show('midi')

Let's predict some notes!¶

First we need Helper Functions¶

In [8]:
def split(word): 
    return [int(char) for char in word]  

def classToMIDI(cls):
    binary = str(bin(int(cls))[2:])
    buffer = split(binary)
    delta = 128 - len(buffer)
    
    emptyVal = 0
    for x in range(delta):
        buffer.insert(0,emptyVal)
    
    assert len(buffer) == 128
    
    return buffer

def MIDIToClass(midi):
    cls = str(int(''.join(map(str, midi)), 2))
    return cls

Then we specify the model¶

In [9]:
class AudioNet(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__() 
        
        self._head = nn.Sequential(
        nn.Linear(in_features=92, out_features=300), # 1st layer
        nn.ReLU(inplace=True),

        nn.Linear(in_features=300, out_features=1000), # 2nd layer
        nn.ReLU(inplace=True),
            
        nn.Linear(in_features=1000, out_features=600), # 3rd layer
        nn.ReLU(inplace=True),
            
        nn.Linear(in_features=600, out_features=300), # 4th layer
        nn.ReLU(inplace=True),
        
        nn.Linear(in_features=300, out_features=35531) # output layer
        )
        
    def forward(self, x):
        x = x.view(x.size()[0], -1)
        x = self._head(x)
        return x

We need to specify hyperparameters and the System Configuration¶

In [10]:
@dataclass
class SystemConfiguration:
    '''
    Describes the common system setting needed for reproducible training
    '''
    seed: int = 42  # seed number to set the state of all random number generators
    cudnn_benchmark_enabled: bool = True  # enable CuDNN benchmark for the sake of performance
    cudnn_deterministic: bool = True  # make cudnn deterministic (reproducible training)

@dataclass
class TrainingConfiguration:
    '''
    Describes configuration of the training process
    '''
    batch_size: int = 16  # amount of data to pass through the network at each forward-backward iteration
    epochs_count: int = 50  # number of times the whole dataset will be passed through the network
    learning_rate: float = 0.01  # determines the speed of network's weights update
        
    log_interval: int = 1000  # how many batches to wait between logging training status
    test_interval: int = 1  # how many epochs to wait before another test. Set to 1 to get val loss at each epoch
    data_root: str = "src/data_root2"  # folder to read/save data
    num_workers: int = 10  # number of concurrent processes using to prepare data
    device: str = 'cpu'  # device to use for training.

This code allows us to create predictions to display on screen¶

In [11]:
def prediction(model, device, batch_input):
    # send model to cpu/cuda according to your system configuration
    model.to(device)
    
    # it is important to do model.eval() before prediction
    model.eval()

    data = batch_input.to(device)

    output = model(data)

    # Score to probability using softmax
    prob = F.softmax(output, dim=1)

    # get the max probability
    pred_prob = prob.data.max(dim=1)[0]
    
    # get the index of the max probability
    pred_index = prob.data.max(dim=1)[1]
    
    return pred_index.cpu().numpy(), pred_prob.cpu().numpy()
In [12]:
def get_sample_prediction(model, data_root, batch_size = 16, show=True):

    if torch.cuda.is_available():
        device = "cuda"
        num_workers = 8
    else:
        device = "cpu"
        num_workers = 2
        
    preprocess = transforms.Compose([  # DataLoader loads images with 3 color channels by default
    transforms.Grayscale(num_output_channels=1), # convert to one channel image 
    transforms.ToTensor() # flatten to tensor for AudioNet input
    ])
    
    # transformed data
    test_dataset_trans = datasets.ImageFolder(root=data_root, transform=preprocess)
    
    # original image dataset
    test_dataset = datasets.ImageFolder(root=data_root, transform=preprocess)
    
    data_len = test_dataset.__len__()
    
    interval = int(data_len/batch_size)
    
    imgs = []
    inputs = []
    targets = []
    for i in range(batch_size):
        index = i * interval
        trans_input, target = test_dataset_trans.__getitem__(index)
        img, _ = test_dataset.__getitem__(index)

        imgs.append(img)
        inputs.append(trans_input)
        targets.append(target)
        
    inputs = torch.stack(inputs)
        
    cls, prob = prediction(model, device, batch_input=inputs)
    
    if show:
        plt.style.use('default')
        plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (15, 15)
        fig = plt.figure()
    
    validity_count = 0
    for i, target in enumerate(targets):
        if show:
            plt.subplot(4, 4, i+1)
        img = transforms.functional.to_pil_image(imgs[i])
        
        if test_dataset.classes[cls[i]] == test_dataset.classes[targets[i]]:
            pred_validity = "CORRECT"
            validity_count += 1
                
        else:
            pred_validity = "WRONG"
                
        
        title = '{3} ({1:.3}% Certainty)\nPredicted Notes: {4}\nTrue Notes: {5}\n'.format(test_dataset.classes[cls[i]], 
                                                     prob[i]*100, 
                                                     test_dataset.classes[targets[i]],
                                                     pred_validity,
                                                     convFilter.midiToPiano(classToMIDI(test_dataset.classes[cls[i]]), 'sharp'),
                                                     convFilter.midiToPiano(classToMIDI(test_dataset.classes[targets[i]]), 'sharp')                                       )
        if show:
            plt.tight_layout(pad=1)
            plt
            plt.imshow(img)
            plt.axis('off')
            plt.gca().set_title(title)
 
    print(f"{validity_count}/{i+1} CORRECT PREDICTIONS")
    if show:
        plt.show()
    
    return

Here we load the AudioNet model weights¶

In [13]:
def load_model(model, model_dir='src/CODE/models', model_file_name='FINAL_audionet_model.pt'):
    model_path = os.path.join(model_dir, model_file_name)

    # loading the model and getting model parameters by using load_state_dict
    model.load_state_dict(torch.load(model_path, map_location=torch.device('cpu')))
    
    return model

It looks like Validation and Test accuracy are similar. Training accuracy is higher. This is expected. AudioNet has not seen the test set during training. AudioNet model training is minimally influenced by the validation set since test set accuracy is similar.¶
